%[text] %[text:anchor:T_803E23CB] # Import a PyTorch™ Network into MATLAB and Simulink
%[text] In this example, you will import a neural network created and trained in PyTorch™ into MATLAB and Simulink instead of creating and training a network from scratch.
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%%
clear
proj = currentProject;
%[text] ## Open the instructions in a browser (Optional) 
%[text] We have provided an option for you to have a separate window with the instructions for this exercise for a smoother experience.
open("Exercise_2.html");
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_11812D39] ## (Recommended) Import Network Using Deep Network Designer
%[text] Launch the Deep Network Designer:
deepNetworkDesigner
%%
%[text] Click on "Import" in the **From PyTorch** option from the Start Page. If you've not installed **Deep Learning Toolbox Converter for PyTorch Models**, you can first click the "Install" button and then click on "Import" after the installation is complete.
%[text] ![](text:image:1f61)
%%
%[text] Select the **folder** that contains the PyTorch model. Click **Import**.
%[text] **NOTE:** Your original PyTorch model must be traced and saved. See [`importNetworkFromPyTorch`](https://www.mathworks.com/help/deeplearning/ref/importnetworkfrompytorch.html) for instructions.
%[text] ![](text:image:2959)
%[text] In Deep Network Designer, you have the opportunity to **specify input sizes.** This may help the importer better assess the PyTorch model behavior, and improve the chance of importing PyTorch layers as MATLAB Deep Learning Toolbox built-in layers. In this case, **enter \[1 5\]** — this follows PyTorch's dimension ordering \[batch\_size, features\], representing 1 sample with 5 features (Voltage, Current, Temperature, Avg. Voltage, Avg. Current), matching the shape used when tracing the original PyTorch model.
%[text] ![](text:image:1217)
%%
%[text] ### (Alternative) Import Network Using Command Line API
%[text] **NOTE:** Providing `PyTorchInputSizes` is critical for the network to be properly initialized upon import. Without valid input sizes, the network will be imported as uninitialized and require manual configuration. If you are unsure about the correct input size, use **Deep Network Designer**, as shown above — it provides a guided interface that prompts you for input sizes and gives immediate visual feedback on whether the network was successfully initialized.
% net_1 = importNetworkFromPyTorch('mlp_soc_model.pt2','PyTorchInputSizes',[1 5]);
% deepNetworkDesigner(net_1)
%%
%[text] ### Review Network Design
%[text] After import is complete, click on the "Designer" tab to inspect the network architecture and confirm properties of individual layers.
%[text] **NOTE:** Depending on your MATLAB version, your imported model may visually look different from the screenshot below. But the network is indeed the same as its original PyTorch representation.
%[text] ![](text:image:85b7)
%%
%[text] ### Save the Model and Export to Simulink
%[text] Export the AI model to Simulink from the toolstrip. Under **Export**, click **Export to Simulink**
%[text] ![](text:image:2d74)
%[text] The app has two types of Simulink export:
%[text] - Export to a single network block
%[text] - Export to multiple layer blocks \
%[text] For small networks with all layers supported as layer blocks, exporting to layer blocks is recommended. For large networks or networks with layers not supported as layer blocks, exporting to a single network block is recommended. You can experiment with both options. In [`Exercise_1`](file:../Part_1_AI_modeling/Exercise_1.m), we exported the network as layer blocks. For this exercise, we will use a single network block.
%[text] ![](text:image:84c6)
%[text] Specify a location and click **Export**. The imported network will also be saved as a .mat file in the same folder (likely named `net.mat`). A Simulink model `my_model.slx` will be created, with the following structure.
%[text] ![](text:image:6dba)
%%
%[text] ## Integrate AI model into Simulink
%[text] If you skipped the import and export steps above, uncomment the lines below, load a pre-imported network and open the example Simulink model to continue from here:
% load('netPyTorchMLP.mat');
% deepNetworkDesigner(net_1) % Inspect the model in Deep Network Designer

% open_system('exampleModel_PyTorch_import');
%%
%[text] ### Generate the Inputs for Simulink
%[text] In Simulink, there are several ways to import data: "From Workspace" block, "Inport" block, "From File" block and others. We are going to use "From Workspace" blocks. We need to generate the inputs for Simulink in the correct format and we can use the left-out test data set.
dataFolder = helper.getDataFolder();
testFile = fullfile(dataFolder,"Test","01_TEST_LGHG2@n10degC_Norm_(05_Inputs).mat"); %[control:dropdown:4c4e]{"position":[39,83]}
S = load(testFile);
XTest = S.X';
YTest = S.Y';
steps = size(XTest,1);
t = (0:(steps-1))';
X_in = timeseries(single(XTest), t);
true_SOC = timeseries(single(YTest), t);
%%
%[text] ### Configure Model Parameters for Simulations
%[text] Open the **Configuration Parameters** dialog (or Ctrl+E) and set **Stop time** to the workspace variable named "steps" (which is the total number of simulation steps), and set the solver to "Fixed-step" and "Discrete" with a fundamental step size of 1:
%[text] ![](text:image:6209)
%[text] Also, set the **Simulation Target** language to C++. And choose "None" for Deep learning library to enable library-independent code generation. This will potentially accelerate simulation. Once done, click **Ok** to apply changes and close the dialog.
%[text] ![](text:image:5b7f)
%%
%[text] ### Connect the Model
%[text] In `my_model.slx`, delete the `Input_1` block, add two "`From Workspace`" blocks with "`X_in`" and "`true_SOC`" for the data variables, respectively. Connect the "`X_in`" input to the "`Predict`" block. Connect the "`true_SOC`" input to a "`Scope`" block in the following way:
%[text] ![](text:image:34e3)
%%
%[text] ### Run the Simulink Model
%[text] Now we can simulate the model by clicking the **Run** button and double-click the "`Scope`" block to inspect simulation results.
%[text] (You may check `exampleModel_PyTorch_import.slx` if you run into any issues)
%[text] ![](text:image:1d3c)
%%
